<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b> Sečenbaγatur et al. 2005: 408. Bulaγ-a 2005: 48-51 also gives /p/ and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ɢ/</span>, but she doesn't present any evidence for /p/ and evidence from Coloo 1988: 71, 373 suggests that <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">ɢ</span> is phonemic in Dörbet and some other varieties, but not in Torgut (as spoken in Mongolia). Furthermore, it is not clear whether there is indeed a distinction of voicedness or, as Svantesson et al. 2005: 149 speculate, rather of aspiration.</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b> cp. Coloo 1965: 74, Birtalan 2003: 216</li>
